The necessary and sufficient condition for a function [latex]f(z)=u(x, y)+i v(x, y)[/latex] to be analytic is it should satisfy the cauchy Riemann equation. C.R. equation: [latex]
\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}=\frac{\partial v}{\partial y} \quad \text { or, } \quad u_{x}=v_{y}
[/latex] [latex]\&, \quad \frac{\partial u}{\partial y}=-\frac{\partial v}{\partial x}[/latex] or, [latex]u_{y}=-v_{x}[/latex] Given: [latex]\quad \mathrm{u}=\cosh \mathrm{x} \cos y[/latex] Now, [latex]\quad u_{x}=\sinh x \cos y[/latex] and, [latex]\quad u_{y}=-\cosh x \sin y[/latex] To find [latex]f(z)[/latex], put [latex]x=z \& y=0[/latex]; [latex]
\begin{aligned}
f(z)&=\int\left(u_{x}-i u_{y}\right) d z \\
&=\int[\sinh z \cdot \cos 0-(-\cosh z \cdot \sin 0)] d z \\
&=\int \sinh z d z=\cosh z+C
\end{aligned}
[/latex]

